From 0000000000000000000000000000000000000000 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: GE-Proton <git@localhost>
Date: Sun, 28 Jun 2026 00:00:00 -0600
Subject: [PATCH 13/13] winepulse: Route DualSense USB haptics to the raw
 ALSA node.

PipeWire exposes the DualSense USB audio function as a raw internal node with
four AUX channels, then publishes the user-visible controller speaker as a
one-channel split sink. XAudio2 haptic streams are four-channel GameEffects
streams targeting the controller endpoint; routing those streams through the
public split sink can leave the haptic actuator channels accepted by PipeWire
but not actually delivered to the USB haptics endpoint.

Keep normal endpoint enumeration and mono controller-speaker playback on the
public Pulse sink, but remember PipeWire raw haptic metadata from the endpoint.
When an application opens the known four-channel float32 48 kHz DualSense or
DualSense Edge render stream, bypass Pulse routing for that haptic stream and
write directly to the raw ALSA PCM path as 16-bit 48 kHz 4-channel samples.
Normal game audio and controller-speaker audio continue to use Pulse.

USB hotplug can invalidate or delay creation of the raw ALSA PCM while
applications keep their existing audio client stream alive. Keep known
DualSense haptic streams pending even when the controller is absent at stream
creation, then reopen the raw PCM on later writes. Avoid live Pulse/PipeWire
queries and snd_pcm_drop() in the reconnect path so unplugging the controller
cannot block the game thread. If cached Pulse metadata is unavailable or stale
after a late USB plug, scan ALSA PCM hints and cards for a Sony/DualSense
playback PCM that can actually open as 48 kHz, 4-channel, S16, and use it as
the raw haptic target.

Also keep the stream lifecycle aligned with the direct ALSA backend so start,
stop, reset, release, render-buffer draining, and render-position accounting do
not treat the haptic stream as a half-created Pulse stream.

